text:
ELON: NO MATTER WHAT YOU DO, 100% OF THE ENERGY COMES FROM THE SUN

‚ÄúThe sun is about 99.8% of the mass of the solar system. 

Jupiter's about 0.1% and everything else is in the remaining 0.1%, and we are much less than 0.1%. 

So, if you burnt all of the mass of the solar system, then the total energy produced by the sun would still round up to 100%. 

If you just burnt Earth, the whole planet, and turn Jupiter into a thermonuclear reactor, the sun is 99.8% of the mass of the solar system and everything else is in the miscellaneous category. 

Basically, no matter what you do, total energy produced in our solar system rounds up to 100% from the sun. 

You could teleport two more Jupiters into our solar system, burn them, and the sun would still round up to 100%. 

Maybe that gives some perspective of why solar is really the thing that matters. 

Kardashev, a Russian physicist, came up with the idea, I think, in the 1960s, to classify civilizations, where Kardashev Scale 1 would be, you've harnessed most of the energy of the planet, Kardashev Scale 2, you've harnessed most of the energy of your sun, Kardashev 3, you've harnessed most of the energy of a galaxy. 

We're only about 1% or a few percent of Kardashev Scale 1 right now, optimistically. 

But as soon as you go to Kardashev Scale 2, where you're talking about the power of the sun, then you're really just saying everything is solar power and the rest is in the noise.‚Äù

Source: @elonmusk on the All-In Podcast @theallinpod, October 31, 2025

ELON: STARSHIP SURVIVED A 17,000 MPH REENTRY WITH MISSING HEATSHIELD TILES

Elon explained that engineers intentionally removed heatshield tiles from Starship in its most vulnerable spots to test how much punishment it could take. 

The ship reentered on an extra hot trajectory and still managed a soft landing in the Indian Ocean after flying from Texas to just west of Australia in roughly forty minutes. 

Some tiles burned through, a few holes formed, but the craft held together. 

At seventeen thousand miles an hour, twelve times faster than a bullet, Starship proved 

it‚Äôs built for chaos and still comes home.

Source: @joerogan

And not because I needed some kind of 'feeling', but simply because OBV and volumes continued to tell a clear story: no accumulation, no real slowdown in selling pressure.

$BTC We had also identified that the loss of 100k would open the door to more volatility and further smoke, and that is exactly what happened.
The 95/90 area remains the most important macro support: if OBV begins to stabilise and, in the coming days, amid choppy movements and some stop hunting, we finally see the first signs of absorption, then we can talk about a potential bottom. I will let you know immediately.

Throughout all this, I have hammered home the same concepts every day: risk management and capital protection.
Every message has been sincere, clear and based solely on the chart.
And in the end, all this discipline has paid off: the reading was accurate and the approach made the difference.

Today, I‚Äôm not so sure...

In fact, I believe a strong case can be made that BTC's original cypherpunk vision has been hijacked. 

Not just because it has underperformed things like the $QQQ's, but because its role as a sovereign, censorship-resistant, private medium of wealth storage and transfer has been hollowed out...

For example,

 ~9% of all BTC sits in US ETFs or government treasuries today; custodial, surveilled, fully transparent structures where individual sovereignty is basically zero.
At the same time, global financial surveillance is accelerating.

From EU stablecoin balance caps, eventual roll outs of CBDC‚Äôs across a range of jurisdictions and the very real possibility of a more interventionist, anti crypto ‚Äúdemocratic socialist‚Äù US government.

What many no longer discuss is that Bitcoin actually had an opportunity to fix this over a decade ago...

The Zerocoin proposal, a cryptographically sound privacy layer designed specifically for Bitcoin, was brought to the community in 2013. 

It could have become Bitcoin‚Äôs native shielded transaction system or at least a sidechain that preserved the asset‚Äôs cypherpunk roots.
But Bitcoin Core rejected it.

Not because it didn‚Äôt work, but because the culture had already begun shifting toward ‚Äúdon‚Äôt change Bitcoin,‚Äù ossification, and risk-aversion. 

The team behind Zerocoin eventually left and created Zcash, implementing the privacy Bitcoin refused to adopt.

Against that backdrop, Bitcoin has no credible way to shield balances or transaction flows.

Even Satoshi openly acknowledged this limitation in 2010: ‚ÄúIf a solution was found, a much better, easier, more convenient implementation of Bitcoin would be possible.‚Äù

He was talking specifically about privacy.
If you go back through Bitcointalk archives, it‚Äôs clear a lot of early Bitcoiners believed that if stronger cryptographic tools existed then, Bitcoin would‚Äôve implemented them from day one. 

That sentiment never fully went away, and as modern ZK proving systems have matured, it‚Äôs resurfaced in a very real way.

This is (IMO) one of the biggest drivers behind ZEC‚Äôs recent outperformance today.

But why ZEC then and not $XMR?

Monero is obfuscation, not encryption; so it is weaker from a technical POV.

Further, XMR's branding as a ‚Äúdarknet coin‚Äù permanently limits its mainstream legitimacy. Zcash, on the other hand, has consciously rebranded itself around freedom, sovereignty, and cryptographic integrity, not as the preferred currency of criminals...

/////

The larger, more recent and timely unlock for ZEC though, is less around its branding but more around recent advances in UX.

Last month, NEAR Intents fully integrated ZEC, rolling out Zashi Swaps. 

This has helped enable native, shielded, cross-chain swaps directly onchain and on mobile (without having to use a CEX).This is the infrastructure ZEC never had. 

And since its gone live, the market has reacted. 

$ZEC has already gone from ~$78 to a peak of ~$800 before settling in the ~$500 range today, and on Near Intents it‚Äôs now out-voluming Bitcoin:

 30D: $390M ZEC vs. $272M BTC
 7D: $168M ZEC vs. $94M BTC

These flows tell a very clear story: since its become trivial for users to rotate their BTC into ZEC in a fully non-custodial, private way, they've begun doing it.

You can also see this playing out directly on-chain.

Since October 1st, nearly 1 million ZEC (+25%) has moved into shielded pools, almost all of it driven by a vertical explosion in the Orchard pool once intents + mobile UX went live.
Nearly 5M ZEC is now sitting in shielded pools.

Another important point: the Winklevoss twins have publicly thrown their support behind ZEC.

While it may be easy to write them off as low signal these days, them throwing their weight behind a new token is very significant.

People forget how instrumental they were to Bitcoin‚Äôs early breakout, they:

- were among the first major BTC whales (held ~1% of supply)
- helped shape the macro narrative in 2013
- provided early liquidity pipelines
- and they helped legitimize Bitcoin to institutions at a time when nobody else could.

In this sense, their backing isn‚Äôt symbolic but also  signals to a very specific class of early adopters that ZEC is worth paying attention to.  

Their alignment with the Trump administration also adds a non-trivial political dimension...

And it‚Äôs not just them. An increasing number of early BTC whales, have started to acknowledge that ZEC is picking up the values Bitcoin has slowly drifted away from. 

You can feel that shift in tone if you track who‚Äôs resurfacing in the conversation

Finally, ZEC has also stood out because it‚Äôs been one of the only PvE assets since the October upgrade went live, not PvP like the rest of the space has felt.

Where most of crypto has been existing participants trading against each other (plus some ETF- and DAT-specific flows), ZEC has actually pulled in new capital:
 
- BTC holders rotating for privacy reasons
- off-chain capital looking for sovereignty guarantees 
- and even Silicon Valley technologists who still believe in and want exposure to the original cypherpunk ethos.

When you put all of this together:

 - institutional/government capture of BTC
 - rising global surveillance
 - Satoshi‚Äôs own comments about Bitcoin‚Äôs missing privacy layer
- Bitcoin core‚Äôs refusal to adopt Zerocoin or any credible privacy upgrade (forcing its creators to build Zcash instead)
 - OG Bitcoiners revisiting the ‚Äúwhat Bitcoin should have been‚Äù argument
 - ZEC‚Äôs technical superiority over XMR
 - the Zashi/Intents UX unlock
 - volume flipping BTC
 - shielded supply going parabolic
 - major early Bitcoin figures (Winklevoss + others) now supporting ZEC
 - ZEC being one of the few PvE assets this cycle

‚Ä¶it becomes difficult to ignore the possibility that $ZEC is stepping into the role Bitcoin abandoned, a store of value with privacy and sovereignty built in.", "urls": [], "mentions": []}, "media": {"images": ["https://pbs.twimg.com/media/G5p8nNfWMAAkwUi.jpg", "https://pbs.twimg.com/media/G5p8uxtXUAAI_aF.jpg", "https://pbs.twimg.com/media/G5p9YLBWMAA0-85.jpg", "https://pbs.twimg.com/media/G5p_daeXsAA7nrw.png"], "videos": []}}}}, "event_type": "post_created"}

text:
zcash's optional privacy and scaling privacy to the planet

a big reason why privacy was quiet until now is that its proponents wanted to appeal to criminals instead of everyday individuals

I understand saying you do stuff on the darknet has aura, but if you do this, everyone will think privacy is only for criminals, and privacy will get outlawed

this is what is happening now

you end up tremendously hurting the cause for the false image of sticking it to the man ‚Äî you are, in fact, sticking it to no one but your fellow man

privacy is about giving every individual the choice, dignity, and freedom in how they present themselves to the world

it is ownership over one's identity

emphasis on *every individual*, not just a few people on select corners of the internet ‚Äî planetary scale

eric hughes' cypherpunk manifesto mentions this twice

"privacy is not secrecy, privacy is the power to selectively reveal oneself to the world."

"an anonymous transaction system is not a secret transaction system. an anonymous system empowers individuals to reveal their identity when desired and only when desired; this is the essence of privacy"

zcash leaves this decision up to the individual on the wallet level

for example, the main wallet on zcash, zashi wallet, shields everything by default and gives several warnings if you are using transparent addresses

it is lazy, low-resolution, and objectively false to claim that a system must be more private because criminals use it disproportionately

while you're at it, what other engineering/math/life advice do you ask criminals? 

this is no different than thinking that TRON has better security or speed than all other blockchains because people use it disproportionately in Latin America

the reason is not technical; it is a network effect from targeting that niche, nothing else

anyone with basic logic can tell you that mixer-based systems (like Monero) are inherently weaker than encryption-based systems (like Zcash)

a mixer-based system attempts to distract and obfuscate amongst decoys, while encryption allows for true vanishing

while they are both much better than no privacy at all, it is borderline dangerous to claim that mixer-type systems will give the individual the same level of security

there is no debate here, this is a fact of mathematics, no different than saying that 2 is greater than 1 ‚Äî ring signatures are great, but they can not compete with encryption + integrity via ZK

a mixer-based system also requires constant motion (including bait ones from people trying to break your privacy) for obfuscation, but true privacy comes from value at rest

zcash's shielded pool has now surpassed billions of dollars and is the largest such pool in all of crypto, one can use it as their private Swiss vault on the internet and move funds only when necessary ‚Äî that is a colossal anonymity set that gives privacy for the masses

and that part is the most important: "the masses"

zcash's two-mode system is an incredible Trojan horse for scaling privacy to planetary scale while continuing the mission of the cypherpunks, that privacy is about ownership and agency of one's identity

it is time for privacy in crypto to stop being a fringe edge case only reserved for criminals and to start being a fundamental right for every individual on the internet

text:
üá∫üá∏üá¶üáπ RECESSIONS GOING EXTINCT: GOOD NEWS OR RECIPE FOR STAGNATION?

How have recessions vanished since the 2008 crash? Global growth is chugging at 3% yearly despite wars and rate hikes.

No synced slumps in 15 years, unemployment low, profits up.

But from an Austrian libertarian angle, this "recession recession" screams government meddling gone wild, propping up zombies and killing real progress.

They channel Schumpeter's creative destruction: downturns cull the weak, free up capital for innovators. Think Apple's birth in the '70s oil mess or Uber in '09.

Yet endless bailouts, like Europe's 2022 energy handouts or U.S. deposit guarantees, distort everything.

This hides malinvestments from cheap money eras, letting unproductive firms linger and trap talent in dead-end gigs.

Prime example today?

Japan, after its '90s bubble burst, weak banks rolled over loans to zombie firms, dodging the purge, and boom, decades of lost growth and stagnation.

Economy'd be way healthier if they'd let the recession do its job and reset properly, instead of this endless prop-up that Austrians warn locks in inefficiency.

Risks pile up; disaster myopia fuels bubbly investments, public debt hits Napoleonic highs with hidden liabilities over 5x U.S. GDP, and zombies multiply, stifling entry/exit and job mobility.

Solution? A tough pill to swallow if you're a populist politician.

Ditch the interventionist crutch, let markets self-correct without fiat distortions or "bail-outs for everyone."

True liberty means embracing volatility for genuine growth, not this fake stability breeding stasis.

Source: The Economist, "Human Action", "The Austrian Theory of the Trade Cycle and Other Essays"

{"data": {"tweetId": "1989289571322908729", "username": "lex_node", "action": "post_update", "tweet": {"id": "1989289571322908729", "type": "REPLY", "created_at": "Fri Nov 14 11:09:27 +0000 2025", "author": {"handle": "lex_node", "profile": {"avatar": "https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1959212888746348544/k74gWWGH_normal.jpg", "name": "_gabrielShapir0"}}, "body": {"text": "@FigoETH how can you run a validator without running q node? numbers seem odd in that regard...", "urls": [], "mentions": [{"id": "134859237", "name": "f1go.eth", "handle": "FigoETH"}]}, "media": {"images": [], "videos": []}, "subtweet": {"id": "1988576679871078745", "type": "TWEET", "created_at": "Wed Nov 12 11:56:41 +0000 2025", "author": {"handle": "FigoETH", "verified": false, "profile": {"avatar": "https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1705499335176200192/zV-9Hj5p_normal.jpg", "name": "f1go.eth"}}, "body": {"text": "Closer look at entities running ETH & SOL validators / nodes.

tldr; entities running:

ETH validators: 12k+
ETH nodes: 10k+ 

SOL validators: 928
SOL nodes: 313 (running in 199 datacenters)

Wanted to have a more data based overview about the entities running the respective networks so I had a closer look and also asked @bw_solana if the data makes sense for SOL (thanks bro!).

I made this research to my best knowledge and with help of ChatGPT, if you have additional data it's very appreciated.

APPROACH FOR ETH
General problem is that the overall number of validators of ~1M doesn't say much about how decentralized the network is since one entitiy can run many validators.

So only valid approach to compare both networks is to have a look at the entities running those validators and nodes (checking validator output).

The numbers quoted above for ETH are the best (convervative) guess I can come up with and they're definitely only an educated (and I think reasonable) guess.

The only thing we know for certain is that there are around ~10,200 EL clients running and 8,700 CL clients (https://t.co/65HDaxO6aU; it shows less CL clients than EL due to technical reasons, eg. CL often sit behind NATs). 

What this data doesn't show is if these clients are validators or just nodes and if several validators / nodes are run by one entity.

So how did I come up with the 12k+ number for entities running validators?

We know by a study made by ETH Zurich in 2023 (https://t.co/BNTeUCOJRM) and by research of rated (https://t.co/gN0264Lbnr) that in 2023 there have been around ~7,800 solo stakers and in 2024 ~5.4% of ETH staked can be attributed to solo stakers. There is also a survey from 2025 by https://t.co/dgDb0xAtZJ which analyzed the number of validators run by solo stakers (https://t.co/fdCBxrUI9l). By combining these data points it's reasonable to assume that we should have at least around 8,000 solo stakers (based on a slight increase from 7,800 (ETH Zurich) in 2023). Running the numbers with rated & ethstaker data leads to similar results.

The rest of entites running validators are more easy. We have around 4k Rocketpool operators (https://t.co/udEgKFVDnD), around 300 Lido operators (https://t.co/ii6dDRfMZt). We also have ~260 Lido DVT operators: https://t.co/Bn8iPFKz7z) and around 400 professional operators like Coinbase, Kraken, Binance etc. (ChatGPT assumption).

This leads us to ~12,960 validator entities which I rounded off to 12k to stay conservative.

The 10k+ number for nodes is honestly just an educated guess for me which makes sense but have to admit that ETH really lacks concrete numbers here. Why I think 10k+ is reasonable: part of ETH USP is that running nodes is trivil re: required hardware, so everybody with an consumer laptop and a standard internet connection can do this. Personally think the number is quite higher but can't prove that. And so it seemed taking the 10k confirmed number for synchned clients by https://t.co/65HDaxO6aU seemed like a good approach.

APPROACH FOR SOL
This was much more easy since validators / nodes mostly only run in data centers. Official number for validators rn is 928 (https://t.co/VO30c0kqzP)

Re. nodes I identified the entities with help of a cluster-nodes.json and letting ChatGPT eliminate all IP duplicates which led to 313. The datacenter number was done by doing ASN deduplication and let to 199.

TAKEAWAY (for me)

- homestaking is incredibly important for decentralization of ETH, majority of validator entities are run by solo stakers
- @Rocket_Pool really doing gods work for ETH decentralization
- Lido really improved decentralization efforts, kudos
- it's not that good that we rely on educated guesses / slightly outdated data for something like entities running validators / nodes for ETH network. I know it's due to privacy / having homestaking / running nodes in the first place but perhaps some smart people can up with a privacy preserving opt-in way for people running validators / nodes to signal the entities? text:
The next Carrington Event could erase our entire satellite network.

The Carrington Event of 1859 remains the strongest solar flare on record, illuminating skies with brilliant auroras and disrupting global telegraph networks‚Äîlong before satellites, GPS, or the internet existed.

A recent European Space Agency simulation explores the consequences if a similar flare struck today: no orbiting asset would survive unscathed.

In the ESA model, a massive flare‚Äîfive times more intense than any observed in the current solar cycle‚Äîerupts unexpectedly. Within hours, radiation and plasma bombard Earth. Satellites sustain instant damage, navigation fails, and the upper atmosphere heats up, expanding dramatically. This expansion boosts atmospheric drag by as much as 400%, forcing satellites into decaying orbits where they burn up.

The outcome: complete collapse of satellite-dependent systems, including GPS, weather prediction, communications, and Earth observation. Even low-Earth orbit satellites, which offer some natural shielding, would succumb to this extreme storm.

This is no mere hypothetical. Experts calculate a 12% probability of a Carrington-scale event occurring this century. As society's dependence on space infrastructure deepens, the risks of unpreparedness escalate. ESA researchers liken it to pandemic preparedness: the timing is uncertain, but proactive measures are critical.

With satellite constellations projected to increase tenfold by 2050, the potential fallout grows ever more severe.

text:
A 50-year-old idea has finally been confirmed.

Stephen Hawking's 1971 theorem stated that black holes can only expand in surface area, never contract. Astronomers have now observed this prediction in action for the first time.

In a landmark achievement for gravitational wave astronomy, the LIGO-Virgo-KAGRA collaboration has obtained the strongest confirmation yet of Hawking's black hole area theorem. The theorem asserts that the surface area of a black hole formed by a merger must exceed the combined areas of its progenitors.

The breakthrough stems from a merger detected in January 2025, designated GW250114. This exceptionally clear signal allowed researchers to analyze the post-merger "ringdown" phase, during which the newly formed black hole vibrates and stabilizes like a resonating bell.

The pre-merger black holes together spanned roughly 240,000 square kilometers. The resulting black hole measured 400,000 square kilometers‚Äîprecisely in line with Hawking's forecast.

Although prior events have tested the theorem, none matched this precision. Upgraded detectors now resolve spacetime ripples finer than one-ten-thousandth the width of a proton.

Such sensitivity not only validates general relativity under extreme conditions but demonstrates an irreversible rule: black holes merge, enlarge, and oscillate‚Äîyet their horizons never recede.

Hawking passed away in 2018 without witnessing this proof, but the data affirm that his insights into black holes outpaced observation by half a century.

["GW250114: Testing Hawking‚Äôs Area Law and the Kerr Nature of Black Holes." Physical Review Letters, 10 Sep 2025]

text:
The Amazon just experienced hot-tub temperatures.

A groundbreaking study reveals that, amid a severe climate-fueled heat wave and drought, surface waters in Amazonian lakes spiked to 105.8¬∞F (41¬∞C)‚Äîsurpassing the CDC's advised upper limit for hot tub safety. This scorching heat extended over 6 feet (2 meters) downward, eliminating any cool haven for underwater species.

The consequences were devastating.

In Brazil's Lake Tef√©, over 200 vulnerable river dolphins perished in mere weeks. Thousands of fish followed suit. Indigenous and riverside communities faced acute shortages of drinking water, sustenance, and river access for travel. The lake's volume plummeted by 75%.

Typically hovering around 86¬∞F (30¬∞C), these lakes had never logged such extremes. Researchers attribute the surge to a lethal convergence: depleted depths, sediment-laden waters that trapped sunlight, stagnant air with minimal breezes, and unrelenting solar exposure. With climate disruption intensifying, this could signal the onset of recurring crises.

Over the past three decades, Amazon lakes have heated up at about 1.1¬∞F (0.6¬∞C) per decade‚Äîa pace outstripping the global norm for freshwater bodies. Long sidelined in climate analyses, these equatorial hotspots are now broadcasting urgent alerts. In 2024, yet another punishing drought struck, once more driving aquatic systems to the brink.

We often think of climate change as something gradual. But in these lakes, the change came fast.

["Extreme warming of Amazon waters in a changing climate." Science, 6 November 2025]

@WatcherChase

People understand a monetary transfer is EXTREMELY volatile. When one asset is sold for another, example A to B, and B is correlated to A (Bitcoin is correlated to the S&P500), then B will experience similar volatility to A until the transfer is complete.

We will see this over the next quarters. Expect volatility. 

- Holding the asset in self custody is the lowest risk.
- Holding the asset on centralized exchange or through proxy (ETF, DAT) is medium risk.
- Betting on a direction using perpetual futures under leverage is high risk. 

We have seen this. A third of a trillion dollars has been extracted from gamblers already in 2024/2025. 

Be extremely careful with your capital. Dont f*ck this up.

Token Narrative:BOBO was originally created in 2019 by an artist using the online pseudonym "Apter" and later gained popularity on the anime board of the anonymous imageboard 4chan. At the time, it was a generic "loser" character representing sadness and despair, frequently appearing in comedic comics depicting life struggles and social failures

BOBO truly went viral and acquired the suffix "THE BEAR" during the major cryptocurrency bear market of 2022-2023, when a netizen posted the "Bobo the Bear" cartoon with the caption, "I told you it would go to zero, but you didn't listen."

Since then, BOBO the Bear has been labeled as a symbol of "self-mockery during a bear market." At the time, many investors saw their assets drastically shrink, were deeply trapped in positions, and were filled with frustration and helplessness. BOBO's perpetually tearful yet oddly calm image perfectly captured this collective sentiment

Players in the crypto community began referring to themselves as "BOBO" to mock themselves and console each other. It represents a mindset: "Yes, I'm miserable, I've lost money, but I'm still here holding on. I haven't left."

This IP has also been hyped multiple times. In 2023, its market cap on the Ethereum mainnet once surged to $245 million, and it has been repeatedly speculated on since then

BOBO currently holds the position of the second most prominent token in the "old IP revival" series, with Wojak being the top one. However, replicating Wojak's success is challenging, buy a lottery ticket

Most traders know how to analyze charts, manage positions or calculate risk.
Very few understand that the real competitive advantage in this market is cognitive efficiency.
The ability to think clearly while others drown in technical friction.
This is the exact gap @vooi_io is building to close.

The biggest problem in multi chain trading has never been liquidity or speed.
It has always been fragmentation.
Different wallets, different chains, different balances, different gas tokens, different routing paths.
Each of these layers silently drains mental energy and destroys precision.
You do not lose edge because you lack skill.
You lose edge because your attention leaks.

VOOI approaches this problem with a completely different architecture.
Instead of adding more features, it removes the mental burden behind them.
The platform combines chain abstraction and account abstraction in a way that makes trading across networks feel like operating inside one unified system.
You deposit once.
You trade everywhere.
Your balance becomes chain agnostic.
Your actions feel native no matter which market or DEX you use.

This is not just a UI improvement.
It is a structural redesign of how decentralized trading should work.
When all your balances come together in one place and routing becomes invisible, your mind stops juggling infrastructure and starts focusing on pure strategy.
This psychological shift alone is enough to change the quality of your trading.

Another underrated part of VOOI is how it transforms multi chain access into a frictionless environment.
Normally you think about gas tokens, chain selection, and liquidity sources.
On VOOI you simply think about the trade.
You stop asking where and start asking why.
That is how cognitive clarity becomes alpha.

This is also why the Cookie Launchpad selected VOOI as its first sale.
Because the project does not just offer ‚Äúmore markets.‚Äù
It offers a new foundation for how perps should work in a multi chain world.
The narrative is simple.
Decentralized trading should not be harder than centralized trading.
It should be cleaner, smarter and more mentally efficient.

If you want to see what trading feels like when the infrastructure finally gets out of your way, test it yourself.
You will feel the difference almost instantly.
Less switching.
Less noise.
More clarity.
More precision.

ELON: HANDS' FUNCTIONS ARE EXTREMELY COMPLEX TO REPLICATE IN ROBOTS

"The hand is extremely complex. There are 50 actuators in the hand, with the hand and forearm.

An actuator is the motor, gearbox, and power electronics.

So that‚Äôs 100 per robot, really a lot of actuators and sensors. Approximately.

In order to do dexterous tasks, you have to have a hand with the sensitivity, precision, and degrees of freedom of a human hand.

Because something that we find easy to do, like pick up a screwdriver or turn a wrench, or even thread a needle or play the guitar, actually requires a lot of dexterity."

Source: @elonmusk, @BaronCapital, @RonBaronAnalyst
